                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d223">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">794A.00/7–2450: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Embassy in China</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">priority</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1950-07-24T19:00:00-04:00"
                            >July 24, 1950—7 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>64. For Strong. Para numbered 1, <gloss target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 15,
                    July 7 re Chi air and naval reconnaissance, pls convey <gloss
                        target="#t_FonMin1">FonMin</gloss> fol interpretation President’s
                    declaration June 27: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“The U.S. Govt wld not stand in the way of air and naval reconnaissance
                            by the Chi Govt, provided such reconnaissance did not involve armed
                            offensive action against the mainland.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>Any questions regarding practical application this directive shld be taken up
                    through milit liaison channels.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Acheson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
